German at all; rather, it was French, as suggested by Germans' usage of the French word Roman to describe a wide variety of genres: pastoral romances, war and travel chronicles, heroic narratives, and courtly fictions. Carried in large part on the coattails of the Huguenot diaspora, these romans, nouvelles, amours secrets, histoires galantes, and histories scandaleuses shaped German literary culture to a previously unrecognized extent. Wiggin contends that this French chapter in the German novel's history began to draw to a close only in the 1720s, more than sixty years after the word first migrated into German. Only gradually did the Roman go native; it remained laden with the baggage from its "French" origins even into the nineteenth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEuropean fictiony17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEuropean fictiony18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFrench fictiony17th centuryxAppreciationzGermany. 0aFrench fictiony18th centuryxAppreciationzGermany. 0aGerman fictiony18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aGerman fictionyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aGerman literaturexFrench influences. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aWest European History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9780801460074zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801460074423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780801460074.jpg  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  